\begin_layout Section
Fisherian model of sexual selection in bacteria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We modified the model by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gandon2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 on good and bad plasmids to include sexual selection on plasmids, thereby
 affecting rates of conjugation.
 To this end, we consider that both chromosomal and plasmid genomes contain
 two loci.
 The first locus 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 reflects attractiveness, reflecting the odds that once a cell contains
 a plasmid, recipient cells are willing to engage in conjugation.
 It contains two alleles (
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

, a null allele not affecting attractiveness) and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

, an allele that makes those cells more notable to any recipients).
 The second locus 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is analogous to a preference in convential models of sexual selection and
 reflects the odds that any recipient cell is more attentive to cells bearing
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 allele.
 Consequently, cells that are not infected with a plasmid belong to one
 of 4 different genotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}p_{j}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in1,2$
\end_inset

) and the numbers of each of those uninfected cell types are denoted by
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t_{i}p_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 In case the cell is infected, 
\begin_inset Formula $16$
\end_inset

 different genotypes are possible, reflecting all combinations of genotypes
 on the bacterial chromosome 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}p_{j}$
\end_inset

 and those on the plasmid 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{k}p_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 and corresponding numbers of infected cells are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t_{i}p_{j}\times t_{k}p_{\ell}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Conjugation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume, similarly to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gandon2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\pi$
\end_inset

 reflects a baseline probability of conjugation, we can then calculate relative
 rates of conjugation by multiplying this baseline rate with the force of
 infection 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t_{i}p_{j}|t_{m}p_{n}\times t_{k}p_{\ell}}I_{t_{m}p_{n}\times t_{k}p_{\ell}}/N$
\end_inset

 where we assume frequency-dependent infection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
